onclusions. I don&#39;t want to create new rules and dogmas and would like to leave it to you.\n\nIn fact, I am in a weird situation. To those who are more into jnana yoga and Vedanta, I emphasize the importance of action in general and rituals in particular and declare that mere intellectual knowledge cannot be firmly imprinted in one&#39;s consciousness to guide all of one&#39;s actions, thoughts and instincts, without specific practices that enable it eventually. To those more into ritualism, I emphasize the importance of wisdom, judgment, equanimity and self-control and declare that merely following technicalities and procedures will never set one free, without developing wisdom, discretion and equanimity. As Vasishtha said at the beginning of &quot;Yoga Vasishtham&quot;, a bird flies by flapping the 2 wings of wisdom and action. Just flapping one wing (either one!) will never enable it to fly into the sky of infinite consciousness.\n\nBTW, though we focus in tarpana on ancestors with a genetic connection, we also make offerings to gurus, sishyas etc and even all other lost souls of all worlds in the end!\n\nThe idea is to offer solace to all lost souls who may have some subtle impact on our mind. If a person is adopted, strong sub-conscious mental connections may be present to biological as well as adopted lineages. In fact, we may have strong sub-conscious mental connection to many other people on account of where, when and how we live. If you can identify specific people with strong sub-conscious influence, you can consciously think of them in your tarpana ritual.\n\nI want to say a few words on rituals in general. Various beings (gods, pitris, other people) have various spiritual and mental connections, and hence impact, on us. It is possible to guide/adjust those impacts in beneficial directions through mental effort and self-control. Rituals are proxies to facilitate such mental effort. They are definitely useful. But, instead of getting caught in technicalities, try to imbibe the spirit.\n\nFor example, the key to a successful tarpana is to think of those ancestors and other beings when you leave water. Think of them with love and compassion and imagine that they are being freed from the desires. There are formations in our conscious/sub-conscious mind which resonate with various beings of this world. It is those formations that influence us. Our conscious thoughts modify those formations (and also the external beings through resonance, over time).\n\nBest regards,\nNarasimha\n--------\nAstrology & Spirituality Resources: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org\n--------\n\n\n\n&gt;________________________________\n&gt; From: &quot;Chandra Prakash vedicstudent@... [vedic-wisdom]&quot; &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&gt;\n&gt;To: &quot;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&quot; &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&gt; \n&gt;Sent: Wednesday, September 17, 2014 11:16 PM\n&gt;Subject: Re: [vedic-wisdom] Tarpana - Clarifications.\n&gt; \n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;  \n&gt;Namaste Nathan,\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;Thank you. So if I understand your reply correctly, while the gotra of the woman changes after marriage, the gotra of a person does not change after adoption and continues to remain the same as at birth.\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;So I am not sure how to advise the person who gets adopted on the maternal side. In the example I mentioned in my e-mail, the adopted person performed the last rites of his maternal grandparents as their adopted son (dattak putra). Now how would such a person perform Tarpana? Would his maternal great grandparents be now considered his maternal grandparents or paternal grandparents or do they continue to be his maternal great grandparents?... similarly for other relationships in the family.\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;Also, can you suggest any good texts on tarpana? I am not aware of the texts that Narasimha used as reference (if any) to write the Tarpana manuals.\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;Chandraprakash\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;On Monday,